# Build output
/build/
/out/

# Visual Studio
/.vs/
*.vcxproj*
*.sln
*.user

# CMake
CMakeCache.txt
CMakeFiles/
cmake_install.cmake

# IDE / editor
/.idea/
/.vscode/
compile_commands.json

# Compiled shaders (generated into build/)
*.spv

# Generated at runtime (ImGui window layout)
imgui.ini

# Ad-hoc debug logs. The GUI build produces no capturable stdout (see
# docs/DEV_ENVIRONMENT.md #2), so logging to a file is the documented way to get
# runtime diagnostics — which means stray *.log files are a normal by-product of
# debugging, not something to commit.
*.log

# Hot-reload: uniquely-named live copies of the game DLL the loader makes each
# reload (Phase 12C). Normally created in the build output dir, but ignore them
# anywhere in case the executable is run from elsewhere.
*_live_*.dll

# OS files
Thumbs.db
.DS_Store

# Development docs (docs/) stay out of the repo until the engine is complete.
# They are working records -- architecture decisions mid-flight, toolchain traps,
# per-phase lessons -- and they change with the code they describe. They ship when
# the platform does; the design record behind Runtime UI is the first one earmarked
# for publication (see ROADMAP.md, M3 completion).
#
# The top-level docs (README, ROADMAP, RULES, REQUIREMENTS_AND_SCOPE) stay tracked.
# NOTE: docs/ files already committed remain tracked -- a .gitignore rule does not
# untrack anything. `git rm --cached docs/<file>` is what stops tracking them.
/docs/

# Cooked asset artifacts (Phase 19B). Derived from source assets + .meta settings,
# reproducible byte-for-byte, and safe to delete wholesale -- so never committed.
# Covered by /build/ already; named here because the cache is an asset-pipeline
# concept, not a build-system one, and deleting /build/ should not look like the
# only reason it is ignored.
/build/assetcache/
